Project Inception Workshop
Project Title: Mitigation Potential of GHGs from Open Waste Burning Under Present Scenario and
Future Optimistic Scenarios: Cases of South Asian Countries Nepal and Bangladesh
[CRRP2022-SP1452-Das]
Duration of the Project: 2 Years (Expected to be completed by Sept. 2025)
Project Summary
Context and overview: The uncontrolled burning of municipal solid waste (MSW) is a significant source of
air pollution in the developing countries, yet limited data exist to quantify the extent of open burning and
associated factors. In many peri-urban areas, solid waste management facilities are lacking, resulting in
open dumping and burning practices. This phenomenon directly contributes to greenhouse gas emissions
and air pollution, which adversely impacts climate and human health in many ways.
This project aimed to conduct a comprehensive review and in-depth analysis of open burning of waste and related
GHGs emission to present a evidence based current scenarios and future roadmaps focusing on two mega cities of
the developing countries, Kathmandu Metropolitan City (KMC) of Nepal (foothills of the Himalayas) and Dhaka
City of Bangladesh (lowlands Ganges Delta). This study will include field survey, municipal open waste
burning on-site experiments and waste sample collection, laboratory analysis of waste burning parameters
in spatio-temporal dimension covering at least two seasons (i.e., Dry and Wet). Further, results will be
used for the development of intervention scenarios and roadmap from 2023-2050 in line with the UN
Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) and Paris Agreement. These outcomes of the scenarios will be
recommended for the national policy and program development and interventions.
Obj. 1: Quantifying and characterizing
solid waste in KMC and Dhaka.
Obj. 3: Understanding the contributing
factors to open waste burning and
estimate the mass of waste burned.
Obj. 4: Creating mitigation scenarios and
a roadmap to reduce GHGs emissions
from waste burning.
Obj. 2: Developing an emission
inventory of greenhouse gases (GHGs)
from open waste burning.
Methodology
In the field survey, a transect walk will be carried out to randomly select the open waste burning from the
areas as listed below; followed by questionnaire survey and sampling of the open waste dumped.
 Households (High Income Class, Middle Income Class and Low Income Class)- 400+
 Institutions- 50+
 Commercial establishments- 50+
This will provide waste generation and composition data. Laboratory analysis of the waste sample will be
carried out to determine moisture content, carbon fraction, and calorific value.
Further, data and information on the following will be collected to understand contributing factors to open
waste burning and estimate the mass of waste burned:
 Waste combustible fraction
 Fraction of population burning waste
 Fraction of waste burning at disposal sites
 Mass of waste burnt
 Solid waste open burning at source
 Solid waste open burning at disposal site
 Waste combustible fraction and population burning waste
 Contributing factors such as geographical factors (population density, access, infrastructure deficit),
political factors (inadequate enforcement of waste management regulations and policies, insufficient
government investment in waste management infrastructure, and institutional working capacity)
This will provide mass of waste burning, waste burning parameters and factor associated with it.
Multivariate analysis will be carried for to know the role of associated factors in open waste burning.
Spatio-temporal emission inventory will be developed based on emission data and nation based emission
factor for different pollutant. Where possible to spatially allocate (i.e., open burning and GHGs emission), a
fine-resolution gridded inventory (1 km x 1 km) will be developed from the national outline/boundary,
national municipality/district boundary, available population surrogate data, and study findings.
This study will also develop at least three different scenarios. These scenarios will be Business-As-Usual
(BAU) scenario, Mix Intervention Scenario (MIS), and Climate Resilience Scenario (CRS). The timeline for
these scenarios will be in between 2023-2030 (i.e., considering UN SDGs. Optionally, it will also consider
scenarios timeline between 2023-2050 (i.e., considering Nepal's government commitment to Paris
Agreement and attainment of zero emissions). This will further break-down into short team intervention
(2023-2025), medium term intervention (2025-2030), and long term intervention (2030-2050).
Expected Outputs
1. Waste characteristics and composition data for KMC and Dhaka
2. Quantity of waste open burning and GHGs emissions data
3. Spatio-temporal profiles of GHGs emissions
4. Intervention scenarios (i.e., BAU, MIS, and CRS) for policy packages
5. Policy recommendations for open waste burning and emission control
6. Better waste management practices recommendations
7. Training and academic exposure for early career researchers
8. Peer-reviewed publications and policy recommendations
Communication and Publications
1. Scientific community: Peer-reviewed papers and conference presentations
2. Policy makers: Policy briefs and workshops
3. Civil society and general public: Awareness-raising programs, social media and local media
outreach
Beneficiaries

1. To inform and share about the project to the concerned stakeholders
2. To receive feedback and comments and suggestions on the proposed project
3. To enhance networking and collaboration with the concerned stakeholders
